 Sagan didn't even talk about interplanetary travel or space colonization (he didn't like the idea of space colonies, and was definitely not into manned space travel). Zubrin talked about Kardashev civilizations, K=2 being one which uses or has access to the resources of the entire solar system. He doesn't consider Orion here, but mentions it as a poor performer for interstellar travel, moving up the long ladder to K=3.<br>
<br>
I first read about Orion from Sagan also, but it stuck in my mind after I read about it from Pournelle, probably 'A Step Farther Out' anthology book.<br>
<br>
 Mainly it stuck in my mind because of the simple logic of Dyson's position: Nothing else makes as much sense when we consider travel on the scale of the solar system.<br>
 All of the difficulties facing us with moving out into the solar system are answered by the incredibly rapid travel offered in <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>big</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> ships, with incrased safety &amp; comfort in the strong nature of the construction possible only to nuclear pulse.<br>
<br>
I remember Pournell said that travel times shrink down to weeks to Mars, a few months to Jupiter or any free-solar orbiting small body, fractions of a year to Saturn. Furthermore, with any other engine, you've got to scrimp &amp; save power, making the most of your engines with gravity assists and minimum energy trajectories, waiting months to years for windows to open up.<br>
 With Orion, you just blast off on your way, taking the most energetic possible trajectory to suit your possible delta-V and where the planets are as you're ready to leave.<br>
<br>
As it is now, we have to wait for a window to Mars every 27 months, taking 6-9 months to get there, with 80%+ of the mass leaving Earth orbit being fuel! Things like NEP increase travel times, while shaving the fuel mass fraction down a bit, while NTR gives you either slightly better mass fraction, or slightly faster trajectory. VASIMR or NSWR is a bit better than either (if it can be made to work). Old bang-bang outdoes them all, and is either off-the-shelf weaponeering and steel work or some new wrinkles in them -no new discoveries or inventions for radically improved interplanetary transport, to revolutionize our way of thinking about space. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brp17>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 202<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/03 10:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=689.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Project Orion Club @ Yahell!</span><hr size=1> Orion does shave of some time, but there's other ideas that work quite well, I first heard about orion from what's in the topic, the Yahoo PO club:-) I joined it in favor of nuclear spacecraft, but I'm still not too sure if I like Orion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 132<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/14/03 1:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddRe